es of North American Labour Movements -- tCHAPTER 13: Ragged Cruelty? Social Policy Transformations in North America -- tCHAPTER 14: Ten Years After: Continental Free Trade and Environmental Policy in North America -- tPART IV: REDEFINING SPATIAL RELATIONS: POST-9/11 BORDERS, MIGRATION, AND NATIONAL SECURITY -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 15: Migration in North America -- tCHAPTER 16: From the 49th Parallel to the Río Grande: US Homeland Security and North American -- tCHAPTER 17: North American Security and Foreign Policy: Does a Trilateral Community Exist? -- tPART V: REDEFINING CULTURAL RELATIONS: TOWARDS A NORTH AMERICAN COMMUNITY? -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 18: Economic Integration and North American Political Cultures -- tCHAPTER 19: Civil Society Organizing Under Continental Integration: The Promise and Limits of Community-Building "From Below" -- tCHAPTER 20: Performing North America as Community -- tCHAPTER 21: Beyond NAFTA: The Emergence and Future of North America -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is no longer sufficient to examine discrete nation-states in isolation from each other. In Politics in North America: Redefining Continental Relations, prominent authors from Canada, the United States, and Mexico explore the politics of redefining the institutional, economic, geographic, and cultural boundaries of North America. The contributors argue that the study of politics in the twenty-first century requires simultaneous attention to all levels (local, national, and international) as well as, increasingly, to continents. This argument is explored through the historical and contemporary social and political forces that have created competing visions of what it means to belong to a North American political community. In this process, new debates emerge in the book concerning the appropriate role for the state, as well as the meaning of sovereignty, democracy, and rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAbu-Laban, Yasmeen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbu-Laban, Yasmeen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlbo, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltamirano-Jiménez, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyres, Jeffrey M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrego, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottomley, Samuel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Janine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkhart, Ross E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro-Rea, Julián, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarkson, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouture, Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrespo, José A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelia Sala, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiGiacomo, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabriel, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutiérrez-Haces, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarder, Lois, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHristoulas, Athanasios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJhappan, Radha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov